SUMMARY:Macroeconomics – Pratiti Chatterjee (UWA) – Belief-Driven Monet
 ary Policy Transmission – A Sentiment Channel
LOCATION:Room 404\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Pratiti Chatterjee: “Belief-Driven Monetary Policy Transmissi
 on – A Sentiment Channel”\nhttps://sites.google.com/view/pratitichatte
 rjee/homePratiti Chatterjee\n\nZoom: https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/84055677057
 ?pwd=q1KyfcUkOWfMfEThCYsc9fs2jh2vCa.1&from=addon\n\nGoogle Maps: https://m
 aps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nThis article examines how m
 acroeconomic sentiment shapes the transmission of monetary policy. Using s
 mooth diagnostic expectations to motivate a role for sentiments in DSGE mo
 dels\, I show that overreaction relative to a rational benchmark generates
  an additional transmission channel: an interaction between excess optimis
 m or pessimism and monetary policy shocks that operates over and above con
 ventional mechanisms. By mapping theory to data using forecast uncertainty
  ratios\, I provide empirical evidence that this overreaction-driven inter
 action effect is quantitatively significant and alters the trajectories of
  macro and financial variables in response to monetary policy shocks\, as 
 identified in earlier work. The sentiment channel influences economic acti
 vity through financial markets\, amplifying or dampening borrowing costs d
 epending on whether optimism or pessimism prevails. The findings offer a f
 ramework for quantifying the impact of sentiment on monetary policy transm
 ission\, thereby isolating the mechanisms that generate fluctuations in po
 licy potency.
URL:https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/84055677057?pwd=q1KyfcUkOWfMfEThCYsc9fs2jh2vC
 a.1&from=addon
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:9a044e39cb540ba9c83775782560444f@generated
DTSTAMP:20260309T033504Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260309T033504Z
SEQUENCE:0
DTSTART;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260310T120000
DTEND;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260310T131500
SUMMARY:Macroeconomics – Marla Ripoll (Pittsburgh) – Capital Accumulati
 on\, Trade\, and China’s Economic Rise
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Marla Ripoll: “Capital Accumulation\, Trade\, and China’s E
 conomic Rise”\nhttps://sites.google.com/view/marlaripoll\n\nZoom: https:
 //unimelb.zoom.us/j/84055677057?pwd=q1KyfcUkOWfMfEThCYsc9fs2jh2vCa.1&from=
 addon\n\nGoogle Maps: https://maps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRAC
 T:\nThis paper examines the effect of China’s economic rise on the globa
 l trade of high-tech manufacturing goods and the capital accumulation dyna
 mics around the world. We study these effects for a sample of resource-ric
 h (RREs) and high-tech economies (HTEs)\, which exhibit distinct comparati
 ve-advantage patterns. We use a dynamic Eaton-Kortum model of trade with c
 apital accumulation to conduct our analysis. Regarding HTEs\, we find that
  asymmetric bilateral trade costs with China play a key role explaining tr
 ade patterns in high-tech goods and capital accumulation. While the lower 
 trade cost of importing high-tech goods from China enhances investment amo
 ng HTEs\, the higher trade costs of exporting to China during 2006-2014 da
 mpened these effects. We find a positive impact of China’s rise on the i
 mports of high-tech manufacturing goods\, investment\, and capital in RREs
 \, despite the decrease in export diversification and the acceleration of 
 deindustrialization. At the same time\, in developing RREs like Brazil\, l
 ocal investment efficiency and sectoral productivity growth have larger ef
 fects on capital accumulation and welfare than China’s economic rise.
URL:https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/84055677057?pwd=q1KyfcUkOWfMfEThCYsc9fs2jh2vC
 a.1&from=addon
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:89484bee9eeb81a11b82576f3460c16a@generated
DTSTAMP:20260309T033504Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260309T033504Z
SEQUENCE:0
DTSTART;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260312T120000
DTEND;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260312T131500
SUMMARY:Macroeconomics – Henry Siu (UBC) – From Farm to Factory: Agricu
 ltural Mechanization and Occupational Outcomes in Early Twentieth Century 
 America
LOCATION:Room 404\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Henry Siu: “From Farm to Factory: Agricultural Mechanization 
 and Occupational Outcomes in Early Twentieth Century America”\nhttps://w
 ww.henrysiu.com/\n\nZoom: https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/84055677057?pwd=q1Kyfc
 UkOWfMfEThCYsc9fs2jh2vCa.1&from=addon\n\nGoogle Maps: https://maps.app.goo
 .gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nThis paper examines the occupational o
 utcomes of agricultural workers during the early twentieth century mechani
 zation of American farming. To do so\, we use linked U.S. Census data from
  1920-1950 and exploit geographical variation in tractor adoption. Reduced
 -form OLS analysis reveals that agricultural workers in counties with grea
 ter tractor penetration experienced improved \noccupational earnings\, con
 sistent with the techno-optimist view of structural transformation and bro
 ader economic development. However\, instrumental variables estimation sho
 ws that \nmechanization directly displaced workers into lower-paying occup
 ations\, with particularly severe effects on younger workers. These contra
 dictory findings are reconciled by recognizing that agricultural mechaniza
 tion coincided with rapid industrialization creating abundant manufacturin
 g \nand other jobs in urban locales requiring similar skills. Unlike today
 's automation\, with substantial human capital and geographic barriers to 
 occupational mobility\, the early twentieth century transformation not onl
 y benefitted society broadly through economic growth\, but also generated 
 higher earnings for the very workers displaced by the new technology.
URL:https://unimelb.zoom.us/j/84055677057?pwd=q1KyfcUkOWfMfEThCYsc9fs2jh2vC
 a.1&from=addon
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:afb6ca33390ac83b1080c4067dcfbd21@generated
DTSTAMP:20260309T033504Z
