UID:c851f6ff9bf32e5b08ba66db33cd9345@generated
DTSTAMP:20260309T033504Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260309T033504Z
SEQUENCE:0
DTSTART;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260306T133000
DTEND;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260306T141000
SUMMARY:PhD Brown Bag Seminar – Hasini Senadheera (University of Melbourn
 e) – Kidney Exchange with Compatible pairs
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Hasini Senadheera: “Kidney Exchange with Compatible pairs”\
 n\nGoogle Maps: https://maps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nWe
  consider a kidney exchange market of two-way exchanges that allow for inc
 ompatible and compatible pairs to participate. Patients in incompatible pa
 irs have dichotomous preferences reflecting whether a donor is compatible 
 or incompatible to them. Patients in compatible pairs have trichotomous pr
 eferences reflecting whether a donor is better\, the same or worse than th
 eir own donor. To ensure incentive compatibility of the compatible pairs e
 ntering the kidney exchange market\, we promise them a rematch with a dono
 r with a better quality than their own donor. We use a priority mechanism 
 to match patients and donors in the kidney exchange market with the object
 ive of maximising the number of matches. We compare the outcomes of when c
 ompatible pairs match privately instead of joining the exchange pool and o
 f when compatible pairs enter the exchange pool and their (re)match must p
 rioritise the patients of compatible pairs.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:34e27d2b4a56ecfa54d45557b6ccd444@generated
DTSTAMP:20260309T033504Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260309T033504Z
SEQUENCE:0
DTSTART;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260306T141000
DTEND;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260306T145000
SUMMARY:PhD Brown Bag Seminar – Paveenapat Niennattrakul (University of M
 elbourne) – Abundance of ideas\, R&D subsidies\, and patent policy.
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Paveenapat Niennattrakul: “Abundance of ideas\, R&D subsidies
 \, and patent policy.”\n\nGoogle Maps: https://maps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKur
 X9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nThis paper examines the interplay between the paten
 t system and R&D subsidies\, investigating how the optimal mix is shaped b
 y the scarcity of ideas. We consider a model of innovation that distinguis
 hes between ideas and innovations. Ideas can differ in quality and are gen
 erated exogenously. Idea quality becomes observable to the innovator only 
 after a costly investment in idea exploration. High-quality ideas are thos
 e that meet the patentability criteria whereas low-quality ones are those 
 that do not. The social planner simultaneously chooses how much to invest 
 in idea exploration (through subsidies) as well as how strict or lenient t
 he patent office should be. We assume that a more lenient patent office ha
 s a higher probability of making Type-2 errors. On the one hand\, by spons
 oring the idea-exploration process\, the social planner generates greater 
 incentives to invest and hence allows greater scope for the patent office 
 to be less lenient. On the other hand\, subsidies impose social costs. We 
 show that when ideas are abundant\, it is socially optimal to incentivize 
 the idea-exploration process purely by subsidies. However\, when ideas are
  scarce\, the social planner implements a mixture of direct subsidies and 
 a patent regime that never rejects high-quality ideas but occasionally iss
 ues patents to low-quality ideas.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:eb1d87761cf3467140ed8cec07a87aa4@generated
DTSTAMP:20260309T033504Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260309T033504Z
SEQUENCE:0
DTSTART;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260306T145000
DTEND;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260306T153000
SUMMARY:PhD Brown Bag Seminar – Ryan Ng (University of Melbourne) – Nee
 ds Based Recommendations with Outside Options.
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Ryan Ng: “Needs Based Recommendations with Outside Options.
 ”\n\nGoogle Maps: https://maps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:
 \nI study a game of information transmission between a Decision Maker (DM)
  and a biased Expert (E). DM is endowed with an outside option but require
 s relevant information prior to making a payoff relevant decision. DM cons
 ults with E who responds with a recommendation before DM makes her final d
 ecision. Three classes of interval partition equilibria emerge from the ga
 me depending on the location of the outside option. I provide a charateriz
 ation of each type of equilibrium.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:82fa2ff47f35f90cd6139c7442cc89a8@generated
DTSTAMP:20260309T033504Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260309T033504Z
SEQUENCE:0
DTSTART;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260313T133000
DTEND;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260313T141000
SUMMARY:PhD Brown Bag Seminar – Gloria Chen (University of Melbourne) –
  Signalling in Matching
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Gloria Chen: “Signalling in Matching”\n\nGoogle Maps: https
 ://maps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nIn many real-life match
 ing markets\, such as residency matches and job applications\, employers o
 ften send signals of interest to candidates\, and these signals frequently
  influence outcomes. However\, under the Deferred Acceptance mechanism\, s
 tandard matching theory predicts that informing a candidate they are favou
 red should not affect how they submit their preferences\, since truth-tell
 ing remains a weakly dominant strategy. To address this discrepancy betwee
 n theoretical predictions and observed behaviour\, we develop a behavioura
 l model in which candidates exhibit rank-dependent preferences and derive 
 additional utility from receiving a positive signal. This framework explai
 ns why candidates may respond to signals and how firms can strategically u
 se signalling to influence preference submissions in their favour\, thereb
 y improving their own match outcomes. We test the predictions of our behav
 ioural model through a laboratory experiment. Our results suggest that fir
 ms do send signals strategically to enhance their match outcomes. Candidat
 es\, in turn\, respond by ranking the signalling firm higher upon receivin
 g the signal. The firm’s strategic signalling\, coupled with candidates
 ’ behavioural responses\, causes the market outcome to shift from one th
 at favours firms to one that benefits candidates.
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:804f9edcfb8b9e58f48dcdd7ea91fc6a@generated
DTSTAMP:20260309T033504Z
LAST-MODIFIED:20260309T033504Z
SEQUENCE:0
DTSTART;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260313T141000
DTEND;TZID=Australia/Melbourne:20260313T145000
SUMMARY:PhD Brown Bag Seminar – Mathilde Bechdolf (University of Melbourn
 e) – Giving a Voice – Increasing Individual Self-Expression to Enhance
  the Resilience to System Discontent
LOCATION:Room 304\, FBE Building\, 111 Barry St\, Carlton VIC 3053
DESCRIPTION:Mathilde Bechdolf: “Giving a Voice – Increasing Individual 
 Self-Expression to Enhance the Resilience to System Discontent”\n\nGoogl
 e Maps: https://maps.app.goo.gl/BirLkJKurX9pSbBB8\n\nABSTRACT:\nIndividual
 s in a group who repeatedly experience that their group's policy selection
  system does not decide in their favor may develop system discontent and s
 ystem disbelief. System discontent reflects individual dissatisfaction wit
 h the decision-making process\, while system disbelief captures the percep
 tion that the system does not benefit the group as a whole. Both may be de
 trimental to collective outcomes\, affecting group members' psychological 
 well-being and their willingness to provide work effort\, make financial c
 ontributions\, or participate in cooperative coordination. In this experim
 ental study\, I investigate whether allowing individuals to express and ex
 plain their preferences\, affects the development of system discontent and
  system disbelief. I examine three different group policy selection mechan
 isms\, each combined with two communication modes: with and without voice.
  Decisions are made either by a single decision maker (dictator)\, by AI (
 ChatGPT)\, or by Borda Count (automated). In the latter two treatments an 
 independent observer is added to keep the overall number of players consta
 nt across treatments. The study adds to the knowledge on the drivers of di
 scontent with policy selection systems and provides insights for managers 
 and policymakers concerning the design of such systems\, especially with r
 espect to building resilience towards system discontent and system disbeli
 ef.
END:VEVENT
